			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Hard LDoN Advice<a name="49696"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 2 04 10:04 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I know your pain oh so well...
<br />

<br />
I pretty much made the same mistake of relying on lull in the beginning. Its nice if it works, but never ever rely on it, I think you found that out the hard way like I did.
<br />

<br />
From looking at the levels I would assume the mobs were hitting in the 600-700 range? Its not quite a 65 avg group so its not a &quot;super&quot; hard, just a scaled hard. Even so, a 63 warrior without proper AAs might find tanking in this situation to be a little tough(I imagine it was the paladins tanking).
<br />

<br />
The monk is 64, he should have his lvl 64 lull which will work up to lvl 65 mobs. I have pulled LDoNs with my monk(albeit lower level, but the mechanics scale the same). With just the lull, the aggro ranges of mobs in MM are small enough that I could single 90% of the pulls. If you find your lull to be failing too often, it might be best to ask the monk to use their unresistable lull, or just have them take over pulls.
<br />

<br />
My thoughts on Chain mezzing are mixed, I only use it in desparate situations, With 3 or more hasted melees beating on a mob, your mezz wont last long enough to be of any use. Using the mezzes with a knockback component can push the mobs out of melee range and save your MA a few precious moments for that CH to get off. From personal experience the effectiveness of chain mezzing is not that great. It would probably be better spent twisting damage runes or AC, at least it will save your tank some hps each round of attacks opposed to a 0 sec stun.
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%"><A href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=844375">Reilna Voiceofwar</A><br>

