			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Hard LDoN Advice<a name="50280"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 6 04 12:34 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Pulling hard LDONs is fun and it can be challenging. Do not rely on lull because it will usually be resisted. Now, that doesn't mean that there is never a place for lull. On some rooms where 4 to 6 mobs will come, I try to use lull. It works enough that I still try it. However, I sing our charisma song to max my charisma BEFORE I try to lull. With maxed charisma, aggro on a failed lull is unusual. If I get aggro on a failed lull, I just fade and then try a different strategy.
<br />

<br />
I prefer to leave a lot of room between me and my group when pulling. That way, on the tough pulls, I can mez one and get aggro of the room. Then I run while mezzing another. Then fade. Now I should have only two or three mobs near me from the original 4 to 5. Then I can either single pull or rinse and repeat. It is essential that you have at least a room in between your group and your pull when using this strategy. Some bards use snare too for splitting. I don't use that much because it is rare I have the song slot for it.
<br />

<br />
If you have a monk, you really should be working together on the pulls of rooms with a lot of mobs who will chain aggro and wipe your group. On the rooms with 4 to 5 mobs who will aggro, a monk friend and I use both of our lulls. I work to lull one in the aggro chain. When I get one lulled, then he lulls the next with his unresistable lull and he pulls a single or at worst a double. Room is split quite fast like that.
<br />

<br />
With a monk and a bard, pulling can be very efficient. For example, even on multiple pulls the monk can lull one and run and FD well outside of the aggro range of the group. Then you can mez one and the other one or two come. Then you should have only one or two mobs to manage if you can fade off the first mezzed one.  Also a good monk bard team should be able to have great control of the mobs. I love a smart monk who when pulling two mobs will always FD out of range of the group. Then I just mez one and the other comes. I slow it on incoming, and I can fade or remez the mob we are not killing. That speeds things up in an LDON too.
<br />

<br />
I rarely use dispell on pulls except for mobs with a DS.
<br />

<br />
I agree that bard slow (55% slow per Reeds spreadsheet with JamFest3) is sufficient. Bard slow can usually be landed much earlier than shammy/chanter/beast slow because we get less aggro from it, and we are often pulling so mobs are slowed when they arrive at camp. That makes up a lot for the difference in our slows. Although I have no data to prove it, I suspect that on hasted mobs that our ability to slow earlier makes bard slow at least comparable with the better slowing classes because any slow negates the haste.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Drumm
<br />
65 Bard
<br />
Torv Server</span></td>
