			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Hard LDoN Advice<a name="50489"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 7 04 10:40 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>For those just hitting this topic since it hangs around the top of the LDON topic, I did write a guide on this a few months ago -- <a target="_new" href="http://www.eqdiva.com/EQ/Guide.aspx?id=79&amp;ForumID=132">http://www.eqdiva.com/EQ/Guide.aspx?id=79&amp;ForumID=132</a>-- been fairly well received.
<br />

<br />
To underscore thoughts of others -- Lull is semi-reliable at best.  Learn to function without it.  One of the most powerful techniques available to you is mez-fade.  Mez one target, when other target(s) agro and come to you, fade off agro from your mez victim.  Leave lots of room, as many suggested -- you need ample room to work on pulls so control where your group is standing at all times.  Yes, bard slow is sufficient since everything in LDON mitigates slow to some extent, it seems - the difference between Shaman slow and bard slow is probably small to nothing.  However, as others have said, you WANT to be pulling and nothing else -- not slowing and not CCing.  You will probably have to do some of this anyway, but the more you can concentrate on one thing, the better off you and your group will be.
<br />

<br />
I finally reached the point where pulling hard LDON became almost 100% routine, but it never got easy or even especially fun.  It was 45 minutes of work for 105 adventure points -- and it never stopped being more work than play.  We don't do a lot of LDON now in our group and I don't especially miss it.  But learning to master this can be the key to improving your gear quite a bit.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
