		</table></td><td class="PanelBodyAlternate" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Hard LDoN Advice<a name="51534"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 12 04 7:27 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>An update!
<br />

<br />
I pulled a couple of EC hards again the other night.  1 win, 1 loss.  In the loss, we had 6 drops needed in the last 30 minutes, and basically went on a 0 for 12 stretch.  Bleh.
<br />

<br />
Here is what I observed.
<br />

<br />
I used Lull a lot from max range when I had good ranged line of sight to 2-3 mobs.  My base CHA is 217.  Throw on my Grandmasters range item, it's 267.  I was still resisted quite a bit, sometimes 5 or 6 times in a row, but I think I only had one &quot;aggro&quot; resist the entire adventure.
<br />

<br />
I will say one thing about Lull.  Even with Lull, if the mob you pull runs too close to the lulled mob, it's going to aggro both.
<br />

<br />
In cases where I had &quot;blind&quot; pulls, ie, I know there are probably 4-5 mobs in there ready to aggro, but I can only see 1.  I tossed a mez on the visible mob from max range.  This normally resulted in a 1-2 pull.  Bring them to camp.  After they are under control, my mez would wear off.  This would usually bring 2-3 more.  I would try to line myself up while meleeing so that I had LoS in the direction the mobs would come from.  When I saw them stampeding down the hall for us, I would fade.  Hopefully, we could kill our current mobs and bring the next set of 2 before they started to wander back to spawn.  If we were able to, the next pull was usually a single, or at most a double.
<br />

<br />
One of the nice things I found out about this technique is that my long range visible mob was always one of the last ones killed, meaning, I didn't have to enter a crowded room to get LoS on the remaining mobs.  I could repull a 2nd time using debuff instead of mez using the original mezzed mob.
<br />

<br />
Morrell makes a huge difference.  That extra 100 range is a god send.
<br />

<br />
Having SoE for most of the adventure helps a ton also.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Leamhanach
65-50 Bard</span></td>
